Popeyes' Texas Stores - Cluster Analysis¶

The following jupyter notebook goes through the process of gathering data about the Popeyes Louisiana Kitchen fast food chain locations in Texas. The collected data is then organized by clusters to facilitate data exploration as well as subsequent model building and analysis to be used for the Spring 2020 course of Business Analytics at Korea University Business School.

The context: Popeyes stores across the USA are experiencing a chicken shortage in their supply chain due to the extreme popularity of their fried chicken sandwich. The purpose of this jupyter notebook is to pre-process data in order to support our analysis in selecting additional suppliers in the Texas state for Popeyes to overcome their chicken shortage.

Disclaimer: Although the overall situation described is issued and inspired from real events, it still overlooks many underlying and unknown factors making it impossible to wholesomely represent the Popeyes Lousiana Kitchen Company's context at the time. Therefore, we would like to ask the reader to take this work as a fiction. Moreover, it is important to note that our analysis and subsequent solutions/advices are in no way affiliated with Popeyes Louisiana Kitchen.

Code cells that contain API calls have only been run once in order to not exceed the free tier limits of the various APIs we used. After that, all data that was obtained was exported into csv files to be then reused later.

# function that extracts the category of the venue from the json file.
def get_category_type(row):
    try:
        categories_list = row['categories']
    except:
        categories_list = row['venue.categories']
        
    if len(categories_list) == 0:
        return None
    else:
        return categories_list[0]['name']

We create a function to automate the API GET requests using those urls and directly add the data we want from the resulting json file to a dataframe.
To better track the process and manage our API calls, if the GET request is successful, we print the name of the location. In the case it is unsuccessful, we print that there was a problem with that specific location.

In [7]:
def get_Popeyes(Locations, urls_):
    
    
    stores_list = []
    for location, url in zip(Locations, urls_):
        print(location)
        
        try:
            # API GET request
            results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']

            stores_list.append([(
                location,
                v['venue']['name'], 
                v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
                v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
                v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])
        
        except:
            print('Problem for the location above!')

    nearby_stores = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in stores_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_stores.columns = ['Location', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']
    
    return(nearby_stores)

Clustering¶

From the above map, we can distinguish that stores seem to be grouped by clusters. This indeed makes sense since we tend to see more stores in bigger cities and urban areas.

In our context, we want to later perform freight/allocation optimization between Texan chicken suppliers and Popeyes stores. However, for each additional supplier, we would multiply the our number of variables by the number of stores. This could become very unwieldy to analyse, very quickly. Moreover, we can make the hypothesis (that we will test later in our model) that for stores belonging to the same cluster, the distance with suppliers will not vary too much or not vary enough to have a significant impact on transport costs.

To facilitate our analysis, we can use a clustering algorithm to group those stores. Clustering refers to grouping a set of objects in such a way that objects in the same group (called a cluster) are more similar (in some sense) to each other than to those in other groups (clusters) (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_analysis)

There are several approaches to clustering that can be used in spatial analysis situations like this:

  • K-mean clustering, that aims to partition n observations into k clusters in which each observation belongs to the cluster with the nearest mean (cluster centers or cluster centroid). This is a very common approach but k-means clustering minimizes within-cluster variances (squared Euclidean distances) and not regular Euclidean distances which is what we're interested in if we want to later calculate the distances between points within the clusters and with their centroids (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-means_clustering).
  • K-median clustering, is a better euclidian solution. Instead of calculating the mean for each cluster to determine its centroid, one instead calculates the median. This has the effect of minimizing error over all clusters with respect to the 1-norm distance metric. The sum of distances is widely used in applications such as facility location (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-medians_clustering). But in our case, we do not want to build another facility or distribution center and would prefer using an existing location as our center.
  • K-medoid clustering, chooses data points as centers (medoids or exemplars). A medoid can be defined as the object of a cluster whose average dissimilarity to all the objects in the cluster is minimal, that is, it is a most centrally located point in the cluster. Moreover, this method is more robust to noise and outliers as compared to k-means because it minimizes a sum of pairwise dissimilarities instead of a sum of squared Euclidean distances (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-medoids). This makes it especially suitable for our case using real-world data which has the potential to be noisy.

K-Medoids Clustering Algorithm¶

Preparation¶

We create two functions to respectively calculate the mean and median distances of all points to their center (medoid) for all clusters.

In [14]:
# Mean Distance
def mean_cluster_distance(data, centers):
    # Empty list of mean distances to the centers of all clusters.
    c_mean_distances = []
    for i, (cx, cy) in enumerate(centers):

        distances = []
        for cluster_label, x, y in zip(data['cluster_label'], data['latitude'], data['longitude']):        
            if cluster_label == i:
                # To convert euclidian distance in degree of latitude/longitude units to kilometers
                # We multiply latitude and longitude respectively by 110.8744 and 95.506 
                # (at 31N lat, which is the center of Texas)
                distance = np.sqrt(((x - cx)*110.8744) ** 2 + ((y - cy)*95.506) ** 2)
                distances.append(distance)

        c_mean_distances.append(np.mean(distances))
        
    return c_mean_distances


# Median Distance
def median_cluster_distance(data, centers):
    # Empty list of median distances to the centers of all clusters.
    c_median_distances = []
    for i, (cx, cy) in enumerate(centers):

        distances = []
        for cluster_label, x, y in zip(data['cluster_label'], data['latitude'], data['longitude']):        
            if cluster_label == i:
                # To convert euclidian distance in degree of latitude/longitude to kilometers
                # We multiply latitude and longitude respectively by 110.8744 and 95.506 
                # (at 31N lat, which is the center of Texas)
                distance = np.sqrt(((x - cx)*110.8744) ** 2 + ((y - cy)*95.506) ** 2)
                distances.append(distance)

        c_median_distances.append(np.median(distances))
        
    return c_median_distances

Silhouette Analysis¶

We want to find the best K number of clusters. To do so, we compute the Silhouette Coefficient for various Ks and select the K yielding the highest coefficient.

The Silhouette Coefficient for a sample is $(b - a) / max(a, b)$ . With the mean intra-cluster distance (a) and the mean nearest-cluster distance (b) for each sample.
The score is bounded between -1 for incorrect clustering and +1 for highly dense clustering. Scores around zero indicate overlapping clusters.
The score is higher when clusters are dense and well separated, which relates to a standard concept of a cluster.

Let's loop through Ks between 2 and 50 and compute various statistics for each to choose the best K afterwards.
Silhouette Analysis can only start at k = 2.

In [15]:
# Empty lists of interesting statistics that we will display later
silhouette_scores = []
inertias = []
means = []
medians = []
k_list = []

for i in range(2, 51):
    ks = i
    
    temp_df = tx_medoids.copy()
    temp_df.columns = ['latitude', 'longitude']
    
    kmedoids = KMedoids(n_clusters = ks, init = 'k-medoids++', random_state = 0,).fit(tx_medoids)
    
    temp_df.insert(0, 'cluster_label', kmedoids.labels_)
    
    score = metrics.silhouette_score(tx_medoids, kmedoids.labels_, metric='euclidean')
    inertia = kmedoids.inertia_
    mean = np.mean(mean_cluster_distance(temp_df, kmedoids.cluster_centers_))
    median = np.mean(median_cluster_distance(temp_df, kmedoids.cluster_centers_))
    
    silhouette_scores.append(score)
    inertias.append(inertia)
    means.append(mean)
    medians.append(median)
    k_list.append(ks)

# To print the lists in an orderly fashion, we assign them to a dataframe
df_medoids_scores = pd.DataFrame({'K' : k_list,
                                  'Silhouette Coefficient' : silhouette_scores, 
                                  'Inertia' : inertias, 
                                  'Mean' : means, 
                                  'Median' : medians}, index = k_list)
    
print('Highest Silhouette Coefficient of ', max(silhouette_scores), 
      ', for k = ', (silhouette_scores.index(max(silhouette_scores)) + 2)) # List index starts at 0 where Ks start at 2.
print(df_medoids_scores)

Final Clustering and Clusters Map¶

We see that the highest Silhouette Coefficient happens at k = 12 clusters and is of 0.72. This is actually a good score indicating that our clusters are dense and well separated.

Using a larger k might results in decreased mean and median distances, and inertia but this would result in overfitting and thus clusters that are not representative of the reality as the decreasing Silhouette Coefficients attest.

Let's use k = 12 for the rest of our clustering efforts and analysis.

Cluster Analysis¶

Preparation¶

We create additional functions to calculate the distances between the average distances between points and medoid inside a cluster, the sum of the distances between points and medoid inside a cluster, and the distances between the various centers (medoids). All those distances are based on euclidian distances that have been converted to kilometer units.

If we keep the units as is, the euclidian distance will be in degree of latitude/longitude. We want the units in kilometers. Here is the website used for the unit conversion: https://www.tceq.texas.gov/gis/geocoord.html

In [19]:
def mean_intra_cluster_distance(data):
    label_tracker = []
    c_mean_distances = []
    
    for i, label1, cx, cy in zip(data.index, 
                                 data.loc[:, data.columns[0]], 
                                 data.loc[:, data.columns[1]], 
                                 data.loc[:, data.columns[2]]):
        distances = []
        label_tracker.append(label1)
            
        for j, label2, x, y in zip(data.index, 
                                 data.loc[:, data.columns[0]], 
                                 data.loc[:, data.columns[1]], 
                                 data.loc[:, data.columns[2]]):
            
            if i != j and label1 == label2:
                distance = np.sqrt(((x - cx)*110.8744) ** 2 + ((y - cy)*95.506) ** 2)
                distances.append(distance)
                    
        c_mean_distances.append(np.mean(distances))
        
    return c_mean_distances, label_tracker

def sum_distance_center(data, centers):
    cluster_tracker = []
    all_distances = []
    for i, (cx, cy) in enumerate(centers):

        distances = []
        for cluster_label, x, y in zip(data['cluster_label'], data['latitude'], data['longitude']):        
            if cluster_label == i:
                # To convert euclidian distance in degree of latitude/longitude to kilometers
                # We multiply latitude and longitude respectively by 110.8744 and 95.506 
                # (at 31N lat, which is the center of Texas)
                distance = np.sqrt(((x - cx)*110.8744) ** 2 + ((y - cy)*95.506) ** 2)
                distances.append(distance)

        all_distances.append(sum(distances))
        cluster_tracker.append(i)
        
    return all_distances

def sum_distance_inter_centers(centers):
    centers_calculated = []
    all_distances = []
    
    for i, (cx, cy) in enumerate(centers):
        
        distances = []
        
        centers_calculated.append(i)
        
        for j, (x, y)in enumerate(centers):
            if j != i and j not in centers_calculated:
                distance = np.sqrt(((x - cx)*110.8744) ** 2 + ((y - cy)*95.506) ** 2)
                distances.append(distance)

        all_distances.append(sum(distances))
        
    return all_distances

Let's create another dataframe where we will compute all distances between all medoids. First, we want to get all the geographic coordinates of the origin point and destination point on the same rows. We assume that driving time one way or the other is equivalent for the same route. If we have already calculated all routes with origin 'a', we do not need to calculate routes with 'a' as destination. We keep track of medoids that have been used as origins to calculate driving time, so as to not include them later.

In [25]:
distance_mx = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Medoid 1', 'M1 Latitude', 'M1 Longitude', 'Medoid 2', 'M2 Latitude', 'M2 Longitude'])

origins_used = []
for origin in df_medoids.itertuples():
    i_origin = int(origin[0]) # Access index in the origin tuple (medoid 1)
    lat_origin = origin[1] # Access latitude in the origin tuple
    lng_origin = origin[2] # Access longitude in the origin tuple
    
    origins_used.append(i_origin)
    
    for destination in df_medoids.itertuples():
        i_destination = int(destination[0]) # Access index in the destination tuple (medoid 2)
        lat_destination = destination[1] # Access latitude in the destination tuple
        lng_destination = destination[2] # Access longitude in the destination tuple
        
        if i_destination != i_origin and i_destination not in origins_used:
            
            info = pd.Series([i_origin, 
                              lat_origin, 
                              lng_origin, 
                              i_destination, 
                              lat_destination, 
                              lng_destination], 
                             index = distance_mx.columns)
            
            distance_mx = distance_mx.append(info, ignore_index = True)

Now we will create the Google API GET request. We can pass several destinations per origin used in order to efficiently obtain all distances. We won't show the request_urls since they contain the private API key.

In [238]:
request_urls = []
origins_used = []
for origin in df_medoids.itertuples():
    i_origin = int(origin[0]) # Access index in the origin tuple (medoid 1)
    lat_origin = origin[1] # Access latitude in the origin tuple
    lng_origin = origin[2] # Access longitude in the origin tuple
    
    url_temp = url_base + '&origins={},{}&destinations='.format(lat_origin, lng_origin)
    
    origins_used.append(i_origin)
    
    for destination in df_medoids.itertuples():
        i_destination = int(destination[0]) # Access index in the destination tuple (medoid 2)
        lat_destination = destination[1] # Access latitude in the destination tuple
        lng_destination = destination[2] # Access longitude in the destination tuple
        
        if i_destination != i_origin and i_destination not in origins_used:
            if i_destination == (len(df_medoids.index) - 1): # Arriving at destination 13, we stop the destination query
                destination_url = '{}%2C{}'.format(lat_destination, lng_destination)
            else:         
                destination_url = '{}%2C{}%7C'.format(lat_destination, lng_destination)
            
            url_temp = url_temp + destination_url
            
    url_temp = url_temp + '&key={}'.format(API_KEY)
    
    request_urls.append(url_temp)

request_urls = request_urls[0:11]

We process this .json file to extract the information we want. Namely, the travel distances and travel durations between each origin and its destinations.

In [239]:
cluster_distances = []
cluster_travel_durations_h = []
cluster_travel_durations_min = []

for url in request_urls:
    
    results = requests.get(url).json()

    result_query = results['rows'][0]['elements']

    for i in range(len(result_query)):
        distance = result_query[i]['distance']['value'] / 1000 # We want the results in km so we divide by 1000 
        duration_h = result_query[i]['duration']['text'] # Duration in hours
        duration_min = result_query[i]['duration']['value'] / 60 # duration in minutes

        cluster_distances.append(distance)
        cluster_travel_durations_h.append(duration_h)
        cluster_travel_durations_min.append(duration_min)

We can now add all those extracted information into the earlier distance dataframe.

In [240]:
distance_mx['Travel Distance'] = cluster_distances
distance_mx['Travel Duration (h)'] = cluster_travel_durations_h
distance_mx['Travel Duration (min)'] = cluster_travel_durations_min

In [29]:
# We assume that driving time one way or the other is equivalent for the same route
# If we have already calculated all routes with origin 'a', we do not need to calculate routes with 'a' as destination
# We keep track of medoids that have been used as origins to calculate driving time, so as to not include them later

for origin in df_suppliers.itertuples():
    i_origin = int(origin[0]) # Access index in the origin tuple (medoid 1)
    lat_origin = origin[2] # Access latitude in the origin tuple
    lng_origin = origin[3] # Access longitude in the origin tuple
    
    for destination in df_medoids.itertuples():
        i_destination = int(destination[0]) # Access index in the destination tuple (medoid 2)
        lat_destination = destination[1] # Access latitude in the destination tuple
        lng_destination = destination[2] # Access longitude in the destination tuple
            
        info = pd.Series([i_origin, 
                          lat_origin, 
                          lng_origin, 
                          i_destination, 
                          lat_destination, 
                          lng_destination], 
                         index = suppliers_distance_mx.columns)

        suppliers_distance_mx = suppliers_distance_mx.append(info, ignore_index = True)

Now that the preparation work is done, we create the Google API GET request. We can pass several destinations (clusters' coordinates) per origin used (supplier's coordinates) in order to efficiently obtain all distances. We won't show the request_urls since they contain the private API key. Similarly, right after we will process the resulting .json file to extract the travel distances and travel durations that we are interested in.

In [209]:
request_urls = []
for origin in df_suppliers.itertuples():
    i_origin = int(origin[0]) # Access index in the origin tuple (supplier)
    lat_origin = origin[2] # Access latitude in the origin tuple
    lng_origin = origin[3] # Access longitude in the origin tuple
    
    url_temp = url_base + '&origins={},{}&destinations='.format(lat_origin, lng_origin)
    
    for destination in df_medoids.itertuples():
        i_destination = int(destination[0]) # Access index in the destination tuple (medoid )
        lat_destination = destination[1] # Access latitude in the destination tuple
        lng_destination = destination[2] # Access longitude in the destination tuple
        
        destination_url = '{}%2C{}%7C'.format(lat_destination, lng_destination)
        
        url_temp = url_temp + destination_url
        
    url_temp = url_temp + '&key={}'.format(API_KEY)
    
    request_urls.append(url_temp)
